67
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:38,720
how we relate to other people.

68
00:03:38,720 --> 00:03:43,760
And that really template is our earliest months, even in Utah,

69
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:47,120
already in the womb, we're being affected by the environment,

70
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:49,920
but certainly in the early years when our brain is being formed

71
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:52,000
and our personality is taking shape.

72
00:03:53,120 --> 00:03:55,600
And so that forms our worldview.

73
00:03:56,320 --> 00:03:59,920
My worldview was, in my sense of self,

74
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:03,680
was shaped by the fact that at two months of age,

75
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:07,040
when I was two months of age, the German army occupied Hungary.

76
00:04:07,040 --> 00:04:09,360
Hungary was the last country in Eastern Europe

77
00:04:09,360 --> 00:04:12,160
where the Jewish population had not been exterminated.

78
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:13,120
And that was our turn.

79
00:04:13,760 --> 00:04:16,000
The day after the German army marched into Budapest,

80
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:19,360
which was March the 19th, 1944,

81
00:04:19,360 --> 00:04:23,200
the day after my mother called the pediatrician to say,

82
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:25,120
would you please come and see Gabor?

83
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:26,640
Because he's crying all the time.

84
00:04:26,640 --> 00:04:28,240
And the doctor said, of course I'll come,

85
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:30,400
but all my Jewish babies are crying.

86
00:04:31,280 --> 00:04:34,880
And so that the fact is that when mothers are stressed or in pain,

87
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:37,280
the infant feels all that and takes it personally,

88
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:40,720
and it becomes part of their template for how they view the world.

89
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:43,680
So that was that year, that's when that year began

90
00:04:43,680 --> 00:04:45,520
in which my grandparents were killed in Auschwitz

91
00:04:45,520 --> 00:04:47,600
and my father was away in forced labor.

92
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:49,280
And my mother and I barely survived.

93
00:04:49,280 --> 00:04:51,520
And it's a story I've told many times,

94
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:54,560
but that's when my brain is developing

95
00:04:54,560 --> 00:04:56,720
and that's when I'm forming my sense of myself.

96
00:04:57,760 --> 00:05:02,160
And then my mother, to save my life, gives me to a stranger

97
00:05:02,160 --> 00:05:04,320
and I don't see her for six weeks.

98
00:05:05,120 --> 00:05:07,280
The sense I get is that I'm not wanted

99
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:09,280
and I'm being rejected and abandoned

100
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:10,320
because I'm not good enough.

101
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:13,440
That's how my life began.

102
00:05:14,960 --> 00:05:18,160
So your mother gives you away for five to six weeks

103
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,040
in order to sort of save you from starvation

104
00:05:21,040 --> 00:05:24,560
in a ghetto that she was going to, right?

105
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:25,040
That's right.

106
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:31,440
After your grandparents were killed in Auschwitz by the Nazis,

107
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:35,200
how do you know in hindsight that that moment

108
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:38,320
of those six weeks created that sense of abandonment in you?

109
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:41,440
I wouldn't say just at that one moment.

110
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:44,160
The children very much view themselves

111
00:05:44,880 --> 00:05:47,600
through their interaction with their parents.

112
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:51,040
First of all, I had no father because he was gone.

113
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:55,040
I hadn't seen him, except very briefly

114
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:57,600
when I was a month old, but there was no father in the picture.

115
00:05:58,320 --> 00:06:00,960
My mother was grief-stricken and terrorized

116
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:04,880
and full of war and worry about what's going to happen to us

117
00:06:04,880 --> 00:06:08,720
and just the task of surviving each day.

118
00:06:11,680 --> 00:06:12,800
She's not playful with me.

119
00:06:12,800 --> 00:06:14,480
She's not smiling at me very much.

120
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:15,600
She's worried-looking.

121
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:16,640
She's stressed-looking.

122
00:06:18,960 --> 00:06:20,560
The infant takes everything personally.

123
00:06:21,120 --> 00:06:22,400
That's just the nature of the infant.

124
00:06:22,400 --> 00:06:24,000
As infants, we're a narcissist.

125
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:25,360
We think it's all about us.

126
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:28,800
So when things are great, hey, we're great,

127
00:06:28,800 --> 00:06:30,160
but my mother is unhappy.

128
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:33,040
It's because she doesn't want me

129
00:06:33,040 --> 00:06:35,040
or I can't make her happy or I'm inadequate.

130
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:40,960
So that separation from my mother certainly set a template

131
00:06:40,960 --> 00:06:44,240
for some of my relationship interactions with my spouse

132
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:46,080
decades later.

133
00:06:46,080 --> 00:06:50,800
But the sense of not being good enough and being responsible,

134
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:55,680
that was inculcated in me throughout that whole first year of life.

135
00:06:56,480 --> 00:06:59,040
So much so that in this book, The Myth of Normal,

136
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:02,560
I actually talk about an experience with the psychedelic mushrooms

137
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:05,360
with the therapist.

138
00:07:05,360 --> 00:07:07,600
This is not that long ago, seven years ago, maybe,

139
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:11,280
when I'm at least 70 years old.

140
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:17,040
I'm in this therapeutic session with the cytocybin, the medicine,

141
00:07:17,920 --> 00:07:18,720
and the therapist.

142
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:22,560
And I know that I'm 70 years old

143
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:24,400
and I know this is a therapy session

144
00:07:24,400 --> 00:07:28,080
and I know her name and I know who I am in the world.

145
00:07:28,080 --> 00:07:30,240
But at the same time, I'm experiencing myself

146
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:32,880
as a one-year-old baby and she's my mother.

147
00:07:33,760 --> 00:07:36,960
And I start crying tears come down on my face

148
00:07:36,960 --> 00:07:39,680
and I say, I'm so sorry I made your life so difficult.

149
00:07:41,760 --> 00:07:43,680
Now that was an unconscious memory

150
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:46,560
of my sense of myself as a one-year-old

151
00:07:46,560 --> 00:07:49,040
that I made my mother's life so difficult

152
00:07:49,040 --> 00:07:51,120
because that's the way the baby interprets it.

153
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:56,480
So even if your mother loves you, which mind did, infinitely,

154
00:07:57,040 --> 00:07:59,040
not that she always treated me the best way possible,

155
00:07:59,040 --> 00:08:00,880
but she did love me.

156
00:08:00,880 --> 00:08:03,920
And can you imagine what a great act of love

157
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:05,680
even giving me to a stranger in the street

158
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:07,440
would have been for her, you know?

159
00:08:08,480 --> 00:08:10,400
But because of her own unhappiness,

160
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:12,160
I can only conclude that I'm not good enough.

161
00:08:13,840 --> 00:08:14,560
And it's my fault.

162
00:08:17,280 --> 00:08:19,920
70 years old, having that cytocybin experience

163
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:21,920
coming to that realization or having that sort of,

164
00:08:23,200 --> 00:08:25,280
having that response to your therapist

165
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:27,040
where they take the role of your mother

166
00:08:27,040 --> 00:08:28,240
and you're a one-year-old,

167
00:08:28,240 --> 00:08:32,000
how does somebody at 70 years old go about correcting that,

168
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:35,040
that sort of interpretation you had

169
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:36,800
of that traumatic early event?

170
00:08:38,160 --> 00:08:40,960
Well, by bringing up to the conscious level,

171
00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:45,600
then when I noticed that sense of guilt or responsibility

172
00:08:45,600 --> 00:08:48,560
in me, I say, oh, that's what it's about.

173
00:08:48,640 --> 00:08:53,120
So it's a meaning to trauma as I define it.

174
00:08:53,120 --> 00:08:54,480
It's not about what happens to us.

175
00:08:54,480 --> 00:08:56,160
It's about what happens inside of us

176
00:08:56,160 --> 00:08:57,600
as a result of what happens to us.

177
00:08:58,240 --> 00:09:00,400
And so the wound in trauma means wound.

178
00:09:00,400 --> 00:09:03,200
So the wound in this case is my sense of deficiency

179
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:05,600
or not being good enough, not being worthy enough.

180
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:10,000
Once I realize that, oh, this has got nothing to do with anything,

181
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:14,800
except this interpretation that I made with my own experience

182
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:17,280
all those years ago, then when I noticed it,

183
00:09:17,280 --> 00:09:18,640
I can no longer believe it.

184
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:21,840
I don't have to any longer be a subject

185
00:09:22,640 --> 00:09:25,040
to that interpretation of myself in the world.

186
00:09:25,040 --> 00:09:30,000
So awareness is one step, it's not adequate,

187
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,720
but it's an essential step towards letting go.

188
00:09:33,680 --> 00:09:36,400
That one belief that you weren't good enough,

189
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:40,480
how did that rear its ugly head throughout your life?

190
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:46,080
It made me a workaholic physician

191
00:09:46,080 --> 00:09:47,600
because I had to keep proving my worth.

192
00:09:48,160 --> 00:09:48,880
And it doesn't matter.

193
00:09:50,480 --> 00:09:51,600
I don't know if you ever had an addiction,

194
00:09:51,600 --> 00:09:54,800
but the nature of it is that we're trying to get from the outside

195
00:09:54,800 --> 00:09:59,200
something that only can arise and fulfill us from the inside.

196
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,280
So when you're looking at it from the outside,

197
00:10:03,280 --> 00:10:05,600
it's addictive because you get it temporarily,

198
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:10,720
but then that internal emptiness, that hole, never goes away.

199
00:10:10,720 --> 00:10:12,720
So it has to be filled over and over and over again.

200
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:15,200
It can only be done so temporarily.

201
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:17,520
So it becomes runaway addictive.

202
00:10:17,520 --> 00:10:19,440
So then work becomes an addiction

203
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:21,040
because I keep trying to prove my worth.

204
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:26,560
And it doesn't matter how many times I may show up

205
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:29,440
in a positive way at the beginning of someone's life,

206
00:10:29,440 --> 00:10:32,400
at the end of somebody else's life, or anytime in between.

207
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:34,880
It never fills that emptiness

208
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:38,000
that my sense of lack of worthiness creates.

209
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:40,000
So that's one way it shows up.

210
00:10:40,960 --> 00:10:44,400
Another way it shows up is if in my relationship

211
00:10:46,160 --> 00:10:48,720
I don't feel as satisfied,

212
00:10:50,240 --> 00:10:53,600
my wife doesn't please me the way I like her too,

213
00:10:56,560 --> 00:10:57,520
then I get angry.

214
00:10:58,080 --> 00:10:59,360
But why am I getting angry?

215
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:04,240
I'm getting angry because it's my sense of not being good enough

216
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:05,760
that's being now revealed.

217
00:11:06,720 --> 00:11:10,640
That it gets uncovered, this self-acquisition.

218
00:11:12,160 --> 00:11:13,920
But I get angry at her because her job

219
00:11:14,080 --> 00:11:15,200
is to make me not feel that.

220
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:19,840
We're getting into this relationship for all kinds of reasons.

221
00:11:20,480 --> 00:11:22,000
Some of them are conscious, some are not,

222
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,040
some are positive, some are come out of trauma.

223
00:11:25,040 --> 00:11:28,880
And in my case, I want that relationship to prove to me how good I am.

224
00:11:29,920 --> 00:11:33,040
So when it isn't proving that, then I get upset with my partner.

225
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:37,600
Except the gap is inside me, not inside.

226
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:38,640
It's not coming from her.

227
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:42,800
So it shows up, it showed up in my parenting.

228
00:11:42,880 --> 00:11:44,000
It shows up all over the place.

229
00:11:45,360 --> 00:11:48,240
I mean, I think both of those examples sound a lot like me,

230
