00:12:54,160 --> 00:12:55,840
and you're not available for your family.

254
00:12:55,840 --> 00:12:59,040
You know, so that's part of the craziness of this culture.

255
00:12:59,040 --> 00:13:02,000
And it's like the hedonistic treadmill in a sense,

256
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:05,920
because you just never, enough is never enough, as you say.

257
00:13:05,920 --> 00:13:09,520
So the last achievement needs to be surpassed

258
00:13:09,520 --> 00:13:13,120
by a greater achievement for me to get an applaud or a clap.

259
00:13:13,120 --> 00:13:14,400
I've never really made the connection

260
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:16,320
that the reason why I'm a workaholic is because

261
00:13:16,960 --> 00:13:19,040
I am trying to prove to the world that I'm enough,

262
00:13:19,040 --> 00:13:21,200
but I think that it's entirely true.

263
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:21,840
Yeah.

264
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:27,680
So in your case, like race and class in this society of inequality

265
00:13:27,680 --> 00:13:30,720
are certainly traumatic, potentially traumatic inputs,

266
00:13:30,720 --> 00:13:32,000
as I pointed in this book.

267
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:36,880
And to the degree that it affects people's physiology.

268
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:40,960
But also then, I don't know your family version

269
00:13:40,960 --> 00:13:43,040
or what kind of relationship you have with your parents,

270
00:13:43,040 --> 00:13:44,400
but there also may have been a sense,

271
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:47,600
like I got with my mom for reasons

272
00:13:47,600 --> 00:13:50,480
and for whatever might have happened in your family.

273
00:13:50,480 --> 00:13:51,840
Maybe you got the sense as well

274
00:13:51,840 --> 00:13:55,600
that even in your family version, you weren't good enough somehow.

275
00:13:56,480 --> 00:13:59,360
So my mom would scream at my dad for like seven hours a day.

276
00:13:59,360 --> 00:14:00,640
And my dad would just sit there.

277
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:00,960
Okay.

278
00:14:00,960 --> 00:14:04,000
And so my early memories of like looking at my mom and dad

279
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,480
are this kind of violent verbally, not like physically,

280
00:14:09,120 --> 00:14:11,360
this incredibly stressful screaming,

281
00:14:11,360 --> 00:14:13,040
one person screaming at the other.

282
00:14:13,040 --> 00:14:13,920
That's what I remember.

283
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:16,080
But from reading what you've written in this book

284
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:17,120
and from what you've said now,

285
00:14:18,240 --> 00:14:21,040
I actually might have learned sort of learned

286
00:14:21,040 --> 00:14:23,840
to that I was the problem to some degree.

287
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:26,000
Children interpret it that way.

288
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:26,960
That's just the whole point.

289
00:14:26,960 --> 00:14:28,640
That's what I mean about kids being narcissists.

290
00:14:29,600 --> 00:14:31,360
I don't mean that in the negative sense.

291
00:14:31,360 --> 00:14:34,640
I just mean, actually, they think it's all about them.

292
00:14:34,640 --> 00:14:38,080
So if your mother is unhappy, it's your fault.

293
00:14:39,600 --> 00:14:40,400
And you're not good enough.

294
00:14:40,960 --> 00:14:43,440
So then you have to go out there and work to prove yourself,

295
00:14:43,440 --> 00:14:45,520
to prove to the world and to yourself that you're good enough.

296
00:14:45,520 --> 00:14:47,920
So that going back to your first question

297
00:14:47,920 --> 00:14:50,320
about how these things show up in our lives,

298
00:14:50,960 --> 00:14:51,920
that's how they show up.

299
00:14:54,400 --> 00:14:57,600
And so 12 years old, you emigrate to Vancouver.

300
00:14:57,600 --> 00:14:57,840
Yeah.

301
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:01,760
By 28, you joined the medical profession.

302
00:15:01,760 --> 00:15:02,480
Yeah.

303
00:15:02,480 --> 00:15:06,320
And you spend the next 32 years, roughly, working in medical degrees.

304
00:15:06,320 --> 00:15:07,920
At 28, I went back to medical school.

305
00:15:07,920 --> 00:15:09,680
Actually, I took a detour.

306
00:15:09,680 --> 00:15:10,880
I was a high school teacher for a while.

307
00:15:11,520 --> 00:15:16,160
And then I was 27, 28 when I started medical school.

308
00:15:16,160 --> 00:15:22,080
At age 33, I think I began my medical career of 32 years.

309
00:15:22,080 --> 00:15:25,120
And in those 33 years, what was your practice?

310
00:15:25,120 --> 00:15:26,160
What did you specialize in?

311
00:15:26,160 --> 00:15:27,440
What did you focus on?

312
00:15:28,400 --> 00:15:33,520
So I was a family physician, which meant I delivered a lot of babies

313
00:15:33,520 --> 00:15:36,240
and I looked after people's problems from beginning to the end of life.

314
00:15:36,880 --> 00:15:38,640
I also worked in palliative care.

315
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:42,080
I was the director of a unit at the hospital,

316
00:15:42,080 --> 00:15:44,800
which looked after people with terminal disease.

317
00:15:46,240 --> 00:15:52,400
And I did, that was 22 years or so of my practice, 20, 22 years.

318
00:15:53,120 --> 00:15:56,320
And then I switched gears altogether.

319
00:15:56,320 --> 00:16:00,400
And I went to work in the downtown east side of Vancouver, British Columbia,

320
00:16:00,400 --> 00:16:03,760
which is North America's most concentrated area of drug use.

321
00:16:03,760 --> 00:16:08,080
We have more people coming from anywhere in the world are shocked

322
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:08,720
by what they see.

323
00:16:08,720 --> 00:16:10,560
There are thousands of people in the streets,

324
00:16:10,560 --> 00:16:17,440
injecting, selling, using, inhaling, ingesting drugs of all kinds.

325
00:16:17,440 --> 00:16:22,400
And people are suffered the consequences of drug use in a society

326
00:16:22,400 --> 00:16:23,840
that doesn't understand drug use.

327
00:16:23,840 --> 00:16:26,960
So it punishes it, excludes it, ostracizes it.

328
00:16:26,960 --> 00:16:30,960
So people get HIV from dirty needles and hepatitis C.

329
00:16:30,960 --> 00:16:33,680
So this is the population, often they're homeless.

330
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:37,200
So that's the population I worked with for 12 years

331
00:16:37,200 --> 00:16:39,360
to the end of my medical work.

332
00:16:40,400 --> 00:16:43,360
That experience working with patients that were in palliative care.

333
00:16:43,360 --> 00:16:45,440
So that's for anybody that doesn't know,

334
00:16:45,440 --> 00:16:47,600
that's patients that are approaching the end of their life

335
00:16:47,600 --> 00:16:51,280
that have terminal illnesses and that are aware that they're going to die.

336
00:16:52,400 --> 00:16:54,000
What did that experience teach you?

337
00:16:55,440 --> 00:17:03,760
It took an acceptance of one's lack of lack of omnipotence as a physician

338
00:17:03,760 --> 00:17:06,880
because you go into the, you want to cure people, you want people to heal.

339
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:09,760
And now it takes the tremendous acceptance to say,

340
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:11,920
you know, we've reached the limit of our knowledge.

341
00:17:12,880 --> 00:17:15,040
And that doesn't mean we can't help people,

342
00:17:15,040 --> 00:17:18,240
but we certainly can't cure them, you know.

343
00:17:18,960 --> 00:17:21,760
And so it taught me how to be with the inevitable.

344
00:17:22,800 --> 00:17:27,600
And you're working with people who are in the process of dying.

345
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:30,560
I mean, by the way, who isn't in the process of dying, you know,

346
00:17:30,560 --> 00:17:34,320
but people whose time is more limited than the rest of us.

347
00:17:35,120 --> 00:17:36,960
Acceptance, you learn all of acceptance.

348
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:39,760
It challenges you to do your best

349
00:17:40,080 --> 00:17:44,400
when you know your best isn't going to be saving anybody's lives,

350
00:17:44,400 --> 00:17:50,160
but it's to help people live a life of as little suffering as possible

351
00:17:50,160 --> 00:17:51,920
and as much dignity as possible.

352
00:17:52,560 --> 00:17:55,440
So it really challenges the best parts of you to show up.

353
00:17:56,080 --> 00:18:02,880
Patience, acceptance, intuition, personally taught me a lot to listen to people.

354
00:18:03,760 --> 00:18:07,280
Interesting enough, people really want to be heard when they're dying.

355
00:18:07,840 --> 00:18:09,600
They want to make sense of their lives.

356
00:18:10,240 --> 00:18:12,720
They want to tell their stories, then I want their stories to be heard.

357
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:16,000
And so I listened a lot.

358
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:19,760
I just sat by the bedside and I listened, all that.

359
00:18:20,400 --> 00:18:25,280
When you listened, did you hear any themes relating to regret

360
00:18:25,280 --> 00:18:28,000
or things that actually mattered?

361
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:31,360
Because I always imagine if I was given such news

362
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:34,800
that my life was coming to an end and there was an approximate date,

363
00:18:34,800 --> 00:18:38,160
it would be quite a powerful way of finally realizing

364
00:18:38,160 --> 00:18:40,080
what truly matters and what never did.

365
00:18:41,120 --> 00:18:43,760
People react to their impending death in different ways.

366
00:18:43,760 --> 00:18:48,080
So there were some people who just fought it to the end.

367
00:18:48,080 --> 00:18:49,920
They didn't really want to accept it.

368
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:54,720
But most people were more along the lines that you describe,

369
00:18:54,720 --> 00:18:56,720
where they really get to see what's important.

370
00:18:56,720 --> 00:18:59,280
And so I mentioned this a number of times.

371
00:18:59,280 --> 00:19:02,320
It sounds strange and I don't recommend it.

372
00:19:02,400 --> 00:19:04,320
But I've had patients say to me,

373
00:19:04,320 --> 00:19:07,600
doctor, I don't know how to tell you this and I can't even explain it perhaps.

374
00:19:07,600 --> 00:19:10,320
But this illness that's going to take my life

375
00:19:10,320 --> 00:19:12,320
is the best thing that I've happened to me.

376
00:19:12,320 --> 00:19:15,040
And they meant a couple of things about it.

377
00:19:15,040 --> 00:19:19,600
They meant what you just said, about finding out what's really important in life.

378
00:19:19,600 --> 00:19:23,840
In this book, The Myth of Normal, I enter you a young man called Will Pye,

379
00:19:23,840 --> 00:19:26,320
who wrote a book called, Blessed with a Brain Tumor.

380
00:19:27,600 --> 00:19:29,600
What kind of a blessing is that?

381
00:19:30,560 --> 00:19:31,760
What kind of a blessing is that?

382
00:19:32,400 --> 00:19:34,960
So I asked Will, what's the blessing?

383
00:19:34,960 --> 00:19:37,680
And he said, it made me appreciate every moment.

384
00:19:38,320 --> 00:19:40,400
It meant every time I talked to somebody,

385
00:19:40,400 --> 00:19:43,680
I knew this might be the last conversation I'm going to have with them.

386
00:19:43,680 --> 00:19:46,800
So it better be a human, genuine interaction.

387
00:19:47,680 --> 00:19:49,520
So that was that aspect of it.

388
00:19:50,080 --> 00:19:54,400
The other aspect of it was that, again, my view is,

389
00:19:54,400 --> 00:19:56,880
as I pointed in this book and in previous works,

390
00:19:56,880 --> 00:20:00,400
who gets sick and who isn't exactly accidental?

391
00:20:00,400 --> 00:20:02,480
There are certainly, personally, patterns

392
00:20:02,480 --> 00:20:06,640
based on traumatic experiences in childhood that make disease more likely.

393
00:20:07,440 --> 00:20:10,560
And people very often realize that throughout their lives,

394
00:20:11,280 --> 00:20:12,640
they had abandoned who they were.

395
00:20:12,640 --> 00:20:14,720
They lived a life that wasn't meaningful for them.

396
00:20:15,760 --> 00:20:20,480
And on death, they reconnected with themselves in an authentic way.

397
00:20:20,480 --> 00:20:22,560
And that seemed to be worth a lot to people.

398
00:20:23,200 --> 00:20:26,800
Again, I don't recommend that way of going to reconnect with yourself,

399
00:20:27,360 --> 00:20:30,640
but people have certainly, I certainly saw it.

400
00:20:30,640 --> 00:20:32,640
So those are the two big lessons.

401
00:20:34,640 --> 00:20:37,520
After your 33 years in medical practice,

402
00:20:38,960 --> 00:20:41,520
you described that you had a bit of a,

403
00:20:41,520 --> 00:20:45,120
you kind of tuned into a creative calling, which was writing.

404
00:20:45,120 --> 00:20:47,280
Well, I began to write when I was a physician.

405
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:51,920
So my first book on ADHD after I was diagnosed with it

406
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:54,800
was published in 1999 now.

407
00:20:54,800 --> 00:20:56,720
So that was 23 years ago now.

408
00:20:56,720 --> 00:20:58,960
So I began to write, and even before then,

409
00:20:58,960 --> 00:21:01,680
I wrote because I wrote columns for newspapers.

410
00:21:03,280 --> 00:21:07,360
But yes, there was a time in my life where the writing impulse,

411
00:21:07,360 --> 00:21:12,880
which had been with me all my life, was stifled and stymied.

412
00:21:13,920 --> 00:21:16,240
And so was I, because I had this frustration.

413
00:21:17,200 --> 00:21:19,680
In fact, I had the sense that there's something I needed to express.

414
00:21:20,640 --> 00:21:23,920
But I didn't know what, and they didn't know how.

415
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:26,640
And at some point I realized, oh yeah, I need to write.

416
00:21:26,640 --> 00:21:29,760
So that began before I finished medical practice,

417
00:21:29,760 --> 00:21:37,040
but it certainly has been essential to my ongoing unfolding as a human being.

418
00:21:38,080 --> 00:21:40,160
I was so compelled by that when I read about that,

419
00:21:40,160 --> 00:21:45,040
because I've started to really understand the value of creativity

420
00:21:45,040 --> 00:21:48,240
in all of our lives, regardless of whether we have the luxury

421
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:50,560
of being called an artist or not.

422
00:21:50,560 --> 00:21:52,720
And so what, in your view, is the importance of?

423
00:21:53,840 --> 00:21:56,960
Well, you're singing my tune here, if I may say it that way,

424
00:21:56,960 --> 00:22:02,160
because I code in this book, there's a great Hungarian Canadian

425
00:22:02,160 --> 00:22:06,080
stress researcher called Yanush Selye, S-E-L-Y-E.

426
00:22:06,080 --> 00:22:09,360
And Selye is the one who actually coined the word stress

427
00:22:09,360 --> 00:22:10,800
in the sense that we use it today.

428
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:13,040
And he's the one that showed in the laboratory

429
00:22:13,040 --> 00:22:15,120
how stress diminishes the immune system,

430
00:22:15,120 --> 00:22:20,080
and this organizes the hormones and also rates the stomach

431
00:22:20,080 --> 00:22:21,280
and all this kind of stuff.

432
00:22:21,280 --> 00:22:24,800
But Selye also said, and I quote him here,

433
00:22:25,360 --> 00:22:27,200
what is in us must out?

434
00:22:27,200 --> 00:22:28,880
What is in us must out?

435
00:22:29,680 --> 00:22:32,560
That we all have to follow our cave urges

436
00:22:32,560 --> 00:22:35,280
in a way that nature prepared for us,

437
00:22:35,280 --> 00:22:39,040
otherwise we can be hopelessly hemmed in by frustration.

438
00:22:39,600 --> 00:22:41,520
I'm paraphrasing it very closely.

439
00:22:42,240 --> 00:22:46,720
So we are created in the image of God.

440
00:22:46,720 --> 00:22:50,240
I mean, what are your religious views are?

441
00:22:50,240 --> 00:22:53,120
But that sense that we're created in the images of God

442
00:22:53,840 --> 00:22:57,120
means that we are creators, because the essence of God is creation.

443
00:22:57,840 --> 00:23:02,400
In fact, we call God the Creator, and we call the result of that creation.

444
00:23:03,360 --> 00:23:08,400
If we're created, and if we're offshoots of that creative dynamic

445
00:23:08,400 --> 00:23:11,200
in the universe, then it means that it's in us to create.

446
00:23:11,840 --> 00:23:14,880
And whatever form that takes, I mean, you don't want to see me

447
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:18,400
do art unless you...

448
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:23,520
I can do a pretty good stick figure, by merit to a nurse.

449
00:23:25,360 --> 00:23:29,680
So that creativity doesn't have to take the form of formal art,

450
00:23:29,680 --> 00:23:33,440
but it does have to take some flow of something that's inside you

451
00:23:33,440 --> 00:23:34,400
that needs to come out.

452
00:23:35,040 --> 00:23:39,840
Otherwise, as Selye says, you get hopelessly hemmed in by frustration.

453
00:23:39,840 --> 00:23:42,560
And so in that sense, everybody's got that creative urge,

454
00:23:42,560 --> 00:23:44,800
and that may take the form of social intercourse.

455
00:23:44,800 --> 00:23:46,320
It might take the form of gardening.

456
00:23:46,320 --> 00:23:51,920
I don't care, communion with nature, athletic expression.

457
00:23:51,920 --> 00:23:56,320
I don't care what, but there's somebody, everybody's got it.

458
00:23:56,320 --> 00:23:58,240
And if people don't realize they have it,

459
00:23:58,240 --> 00:24:00,640
it's only because life has hemmed them in and they're too busy.

460
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:04,320
And sometimes they are trying to make a living or trying to survive

461
00:24:04,320 --> 00:24:06,000
or to disconnect it from themselves.

462
00:24:06,640 --> 00:24:07,760
But it's in all of us.

463
00:24:07,760 --> 00:24:11,520
And to the extent that we don't give it expression, we suffer.

464
00:24:13,040 --> 00:24:18,160
One of the things that really hems it in is the prospect

465
00:24:18,160 --> 00:24:20,080
that we might not be good at it,

466
00:24:20,080 --> 00:24:21,920
because we think to express ourselves creatively,

467
00:24:21,920 --> 00:24:23,840
we kind of join a competition of sorts.

468
00:24:24,400 --> 00:24:26,000
And that's a trap we can fall into.

469
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:29,120
So if I'm going to DJ, I need to become a good DJ,

470
00:24:29,120 --> 00:24:31,440
but in social comparison or else I don't want to...

471
00:24:31,440 --> 00:24:33,200
But what I've come to learn is, in fact,

472
00:24:33,200 --> 00:24:37,520
the act of DJing alone in my kitchen at midnight is the reward.

473
00:24:38,160 --> 00:24:40,560
Regardless of outcome or whether there's a crowd there,

474
00:24:40,560 --> 00:24:41,840
it's just me and my dog listening.

475
00:24:42,880 --> 00:24:44,080
The expression is the reward,

476
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:46,560
not the achievement or the medal that I might get.

477
00:24:46,560 --> 00:24:47,840
Yeah, not the external.

478
00:24:47,840 --> 00:24:50,560
Well, look, I went through that in the writing of this book.

479
00:24:50,560 --> 00:24:56,160
So here I am, this writer who writes about trauma and healing.

480
00:24:56,160 --> 00:24:59,120
And all of a sudden I'm in a panic because I'm writing a book.

481
00:24:59,680 --> 00:25:03,840
And I realized that the problem was that you talked about identifying with your work.

482
00:25:03,840 --> 00:25:05,360
So I had identified with this book.

483
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:07,920
So the problem wasn't the book.

484
00:25:09,040 --> 00:25:11,360
Because let's say I write the book and it's not a success.

485
00:25:11,360 --> 00:25:14,480
I mean, okay, big headline in the Sunday Times.

486
00:25:15,120 --> 00:25:16,480
Book, not a big success.

487
00:25:17,360 --> 00:25:19,760
How big a big deal is that in the history of the universe?

488
00:25:20,640 --> 00:25:24,480
But if I identify with the book and it's not going well,

489
00:25:24,480 --> 00:25:26,960
then if the book fails, then I'm feeling as a person,

490
00:25:26,960 --> 00:25:31,200
which then goes back to my very earliest concern about not being worth it.

491
00:25:32,160 --> 00:25:37,440
So once I disidentified, once I said, no, this is just a book.

492
00:25:38,080 --> 00:25:40,160
It may be a good book, it may be an important book,

493
00:25:40,160 --> 00:25:44,080
maybe a book that doesn't hit the mark, but it's only a book.

494
00:25:44,640 --> 00:25:48,000
And how it goes says nothing about me or my worth.

495
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:51,920
Once I could decouple that, then I could confidently and much more comfortably

496
00:25:51,920 --> 00:25:53,120
go back to the writing of it.

497
00:25:53,120 --> 00:25:54,240
But I went through that crisis.

